"1324","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1440":"1440","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1328":"1328","Buxton, Derbyshire, England":"Buxton, Derbyshire, England","Sedgebrook, Lincolnshire, England":"Sedgebrook, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Holme Pierrepont, Nottinghamshire, England":"Holme Pierrepont, Nottinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bourdon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French:","nickname from Old French <i>bourdon</i>, a word with several meanings, from any or each of which the surname could have arisen: ‘pilgrim's staff’, denoting a pilgrim; ‘bumblebee’, denoting someone thought to resemble the insect in some way; and ‘bagpipes’, denoting a piper or pipe-maker. It is also found in England, as a surname of Huguenot origin (compare   Burden  ).","habitational name from (Le) Bourdon, the name of several places in various parts of France."],"variants":[{"name":"Bourdo","meanings":["Altered form of French   Bourdon  ."]},{"name":"Burden","meanings":["English:","(southern England, of Norman origin): from a diminutive of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Burdo</i>, for which compare   Burdett  . <i>Burdonus</i> and other derivatives of the Gaulish personal name <i>Burdo</i> (‘mule’) are found in France, where it is rare and the similar French surname may derive instead from Old French <i>bourdon</i> in the sense ‘pilgrim's staff’ (compare   Bourdon   1). The personal name, whether of ancient Germanic or Gaulish origin, does occur in medieval England, but rarely.","habitational name from any of various places called Burdon or Burden. Burden in Yorkshire and Great Burdon in County Durham are named with Old English <i>burh</i> ‘stronghold, fortified place’ + <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’; Burdon in Tyne and Wear is named with Old English <i>b̄re</i> ‘byre’ + <i>denu</i> ‘valley’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":3,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":12,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":57,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John Bourdon V was born in 1325, in Buxton, Derbyshire, England, his father, John Bourdon IV, was 25 and his mother, Unknown, was 20. He had at least 1 son with Mrs John Bourdon. He died in Holme Pierrepont, Nottinghamshire, England."},"et":{"1325–":"1325–Surnud","1325–Male":"1325–Surnud","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","1360–1440":"1360–1440","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1305–Female":"1305–Surnud","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1324":"1324","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1440":"1440","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1328":"1328","Buxton, Derbyshire, England":"Bux